  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_5_1">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The vector and parametric forms of a line allow us to easily describe line segments in space.
      </p>

      <p>
        Let <m>P_1 = (1,2,-1)</m> and <m>P_2 = (-2,1,-2)</m>, and let <m>\mathcal{L}</m> be the line in <m>\R^3</m> through <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> as in <xref ref="ActLines3D1">Activity</xref>.
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              What value of the parameter <m>t</m> makes <m>(x(t), y(t), z(t)) = P_1</m>? What value of <m>t</m> makes <m>(x(t), y(t), z(t)) = P_2</m>?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              What <m>t</m> values describe the line segment between the points <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m>?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              What about the line segment (along the same line) from <m>(7,4,1)</m> to <m>(-8,-1,-4)</m>?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Now, consider a segment that lies on a different line:  parameterize the segment that connects point <m>R=(4,-2,7)</m> to <m>Q=(-11,4,27)</m> in such a way that <m>t = 0</m> corresponds to point <m>Q</m>, while <m>t = 2</m> corresponds to <m>R</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <answer>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              The parameter <m>t</m> that makes <m>(x(t), y(t), z(t)) = P_1</m> is <m>t = 0</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
              The parameter <m>t</m> that makes <m>(x(t), y(t), z(t)) = P_2</m> is <m>t = 1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The line segment between points <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> is defined by <m>0 \leq t \leq 1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The line segment between points <m>(7, 4, 1)</m> and <m>(-8, -1, -4)</m> is defined by <m>-2 \leq t \leq 3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x(t) = -11 + \frac{15}{2}t, y(t) = 4 - 3t, z(t) = 17 + 5t</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </answer>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              From activity 9.5.2, <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_1} = \langle -3, -1, -1 \rangle</m>. The vector form of the line through <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> is <m>\vr(t) = \langle 1, 2, -1\rangle + t * \langle-3, -1, -1\rangle</m>. Using parametric equations, this is equal to <m>x(t) = 1 - 3t, y(t) = 2 - t, z(t) = -1 - t</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
              To find the corresponding t-values for each point, set each coordinate equal to the corresponding parametric equation. <m>1 = 1 - 3t, 2 = 2 - t, -1 = -1 -t</m>. Solve each equation to get <m>t = 0</m>. For <m>P_2, -2 = 1 - 3t, 1 = 2 - t, -2 = -1 - t</m>. Solve each equation to get <m>t = 1</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              All the points between <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> will have <m>t</m>-values between <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 1</m>. Therefore, the line segment between <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> is defined for <m>0 \leq t \leq 1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              For <m>P_3, 7 = 1 - 3t, 4 = 2 - t, 1 = -1 -t</m>. Solve each equation to get <m>t = -2</m>. For <m>P_4, -8 = 1 - 3t, -1 = 2 - t, -4 = -1 - t</m>. Solve each equation to get <m>t = 3</m>. 
            </p>

            <p>
              Therefore, line segment between points <m>(7, 4, 1)</m> and <m>(-8, -1, -4)</m> is defined by <m>-2 \leq t \leq 3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\overrightarrow{QR} = \langle 15, -6, -20 \rangle</m>. We need to find a scalar (direction) vector in the direction of <m>\langle 15, -6, -20 \rangle</m>. If point <m>Q</m> is the initial point, then <m>\vr(t) = \langle -11, 4, 27 \rangle + t * \langle 15v, -6v, -20v \rangle</m>. When <m>t = 2, \langle 4, -2, 7 \rangle = \langle -11, 4, 27 \rangle + (2) * \langle 15v, -6v, -20v \rangle</m>. Solve for <m>v</m> to get <m>v = \frac{1}{2}</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
              Therefore, <m>\vr(t) = \langle -11, 4, 27 \rangle + t * \langle 15 * \frac{1}{2} , -6 * \frac{1}{2}, -20 * \frac{1}{2} \rangle</m>. This cooresponds to parametric equations <m>x(t) = -11 + \frac{15}{2}t, y(t) = 4 - 3t, z(t) = 27 -10t</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_5_2">
    <statement>
      <p>
        This exercise explores key relationships between a pair of lines. Consider the following two lines: one with parametric equations <m>x(s) = 4-2s</m>, <m>y(s) = -2 + s</m>, <m>z(s) = 1 + 3s</m>, and the other being the line through <m>(-4, 2, 17)</m> in the direction <m>\vv = \langle -2, 1, 5 \rangle</m>.
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              Find a direction vector for the first line, which is given in parametric form.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find parametric equations for the second line, written in terms of the parameter <m>t</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Show that the two lines intersect at a single point by finding the values of <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> that result in the same point. Then find the point of intersection.  
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the acute angle formed where the two lines intersect, noting that this angle will be given by the acute angle between their respective direction vectors.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find an equation for the plane that contains both of the lines described in this problem.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <answer>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\langle -2, 1, 3 \rangle</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x(t) = -4 - 2t, y(t) = 2 + t, z(t) = 17 + 5t</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>s = 2, t = -2</m>. The point of intersection is <m>(0, 0, 7)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The angle formed where the two lines intersect is <m>12.60^{\circ}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2(x - 4) + 4(y + 2) = 0</m> or <m>2(x + 4) + 4(y - 2) = 0</m> or <m>2x + 4y = 0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </answer>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              Identify the coefficients in front of the <m>s</m> terms. <m>\langle -2, 1, 3 \rangle</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x(t) = -4 - 2t, y(t) = 2 + t, z(t) = 17 + 5t</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Write a system of two equations by setting the first two corresponding parametric equations equal to each other for each line <m>4 - 2s = -4 - 2t, -2 + s = 2 + t</m>. Solve to get <m>s = 2, t = -2</m>. Plug <m>s = 2</m> or <m>t = -2</m> into either set of parametric equations to get the point <m>(0, 0, 7)</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The angle between the unit vectors is <m>\theta = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{\vu\cdot\vv}{|\vu||\vv|}\right) = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{(-2)(-2) + (1)(1) + (3)(5)}{|\sqrt{14}||\sqrt{30}|}\right) = 12.60^{\circ}</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the normal vector to the two direction vectors. <m>\vu \times \vv = ((1)(5) - (3)(1))\vi - ((-2)(5) - (3)(-2))\vj + ((-2)(1) - (-2)(1))\vk = \langle 2, 4, 0 \rangle</m>. Use either <m>(4, -2, 1)</m> or <m>(-4, 2, 17)</m> and <m>\langle 2, 4, 0 \rangle</m> to write the scalar equation of the plane <m>2(x + 4) + 4(y - 2) + 0(z - 17) = 2(x + 4) + 4(y - 2) = 0</m> or <m>2(x - 4) + 4(y + 2) + 0(z - 1) = 2(x - 4) + 4(y + 2) = 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_5_3">
    <statement>
      <p>
        This exercise explores key relationships between a pair of planes. Consider the following two planes: one with scalar equation <m>4x - 5y + z = -2</m>, and the other which passes through the points <m>(1,1,1)</m>, <m>(0,1,-1)</m>, and <m>(4, 2, -1)</m>.
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              Find a vector normal to the first plane.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find a scalar equation for the second plane.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the angle between the planes, where the angle between them is defined by the angle between their respective normal vectors.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find a point that lies on both planes.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Since these two planes do not have parallel normal vectors, the planes must intersect, and thus must intersect in a line.  Observe that the line of intersection lies in both planes, and thus the direction vector of the line must be perpendicular to each of the respective normal vectors of the two planes.  Find a direction vector for the line of intersection for the two planes.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Determine parametric equations for the line of intersection of the two planes.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <answer>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\vn = \langle 4, -5, 1 \rangle</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2(x - 1) - 8(y - 1) - (z - 1) = 0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>29.18^{\circ}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>(0, \frac{9}{13}, -\frac{-19}{13})</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\vn \times \vm = \langle 13, 6, -22 \rangle</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Answer depends on the point found in (d). <m>x(t) = 13t, y(t) = \frac{9}{13} + 6t, z(t) = -\frac{19}{13} - 22t</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </answer>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              The coefficients in front of the variables identify the normal vector <m>\vn = \langle 4, -5, 1 \rangle</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The vector from <m>(1, 1, 1)</m> to <m>(0, 1, -1)</m> is <m>\langle -1, 0, -2 \rangle</m>. The vector from <m>(1, 1, 1)</m> to <m>(4, 2, -1)</m> is <m>\langle 3, 1, -2 \rangle</m>. 
            </p>

            <p>
              The cross product of the vectors is <m>((0)(-2) - (-2)(1))\vi - ((-1)(-2) - (-2)(3))\vj + ((-1)(1) - (0)(3))\vk = \langle 2, -8, -1 \rangle</m>. 
            </p>

            <p>
              Therefore, the equation of the line is <m>2(x - 1) - 8(y - 1) - (z - 1) = 0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the angle between the normal vectors. <m>\theta = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{\vu\cdot\vv}{|\vu||\vv|}\right) = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{(4)(2) + (-5)(-8) + (1)(-1)}{|\sqrt{42}||\sqrt{69}|}\right) = 29.18^{\circ}</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Rewrite the scalar equation from <m>b.</m> as <m>2x - 2 - 8y + 8 -z + 1 = 2x - 8y -z + 7 = 0</m>. Rewrite as <m>2x - 8y -z = -7</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
              We have a system of 2 equations with 3 variables. If we add the equations, we get <m>6x - 13y = -9</m>. Choose an <m>x</m>-value and solve for <m>y</m>. Let <m>x = 0</m>. Then <m>y = \frac{9}{13}</m>. Plug these values into either equation then solve for <m>z</m> to get <m>z = -\frac{19}{13}</m>. This point is <m>(0, \frac{9}{13}, -\frac{-19}{13})</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the cross product of the normal vectors. <m>\langle 4, -5, 1 \rangle \times \langle 2, -8, -1 \rangle = \langle 13, 6, -22 \rangle</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Using the point found in (d) and the normal vector from (e), <m>x(t) = 13t, y(t) = \frac{9}{13} + 6t, z(t) = -\frac{19}{13} - 22t</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
    
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_5_4">
    <statement>
      <p>
        In this problem, we explore how we can use what we know about vectors and projections to find the distance from a point to a
        plane.
      </p>

      <p>
        Let <m>p</m> be the plane with equation <m>z=-4x+3y+4</m>, and let
        <m>Q = (4,-1,8)</m>.
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that <m>Q</m> does not lie in the plane <m>p</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find a normal vector <m>\vn</m> to the plane <m>p</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the coordinates of a point <m>P</m> in <m>p</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the components of <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m>. Draw a picture to illustrate the objects found so far.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Explain why <m>|\comp_{\vn} \overrightarrow{PQ}|</m> gives the distance from the point <m>Q</m> to the plane <m>p</m>. Find this distance.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <answer>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              Plug in <m>x = 4</m> and <m>y = -1</m> to the given equation. The output is not equal to <m>8</m>, so <m>Q</m> does not lie in the plane <m>p</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\vn = \langle -4, 3, -1 \rangle</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              A point in <m>p</m> is <m>(0, 0, 4)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\overrightarrow{PQ} = \langle 4, -1, 4 \rangle</m>. Then sketch a picture.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Draw <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> with an initial point <m>P</m> in plane <m>p</m> and terminal point <m>Q</m> in a different plane that contains <m>Q</m>. Then construct a normal vector in plane <m>p</m>, from plane <m>p</m> to the point <m>Q</m>. The length of the projection of <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> onto the normal vector is <m>|\comp_{\vn} \overrightarrow{PQ}| = |-\frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}| = \frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}</m>. The distance from point <m>Q</m> to the plane <m>p</m> is <m>\frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              Plug in <m>x = 4</m> and <m>y = -1</m> to the given equation. <m>z = -4(4) + 3(-1) + 4 = -15</m> which is not equal to <m>8</m>. Therefore <m>Q</m> does not lie in the plane <m>p</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The normal vector can be identified by looking at the coefficients of the variables in scalar form. <m>-4x + 3y -z + 4 = 0</m> has a normal vector of <m>\langle -4, 3, -1 \rangle</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Choose any <m>x</m>-value and <m>y</m>-value. Then find the corresponding <m>z</m>-value. Let <m>x = 0, y = 0</m>, then <m>z = 4</m>. The point is <m>(0, 0, 4)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\overrightarrow{PQ} = \langle 4 - 0, -1 - 0, 8 - 4 \rangle = \langle 4, -1, 4 \rangle</m>. Then sketch a picture.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Draw <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> with an initial point <m>P</m> in plane <m>p</m> and terminal point <m>Q</m> in a different plane that contains <m>Q</m>. Then construct a normal vector in plane <m>p</m>, from plane <m>p</m> to the point <m>Q</m>. The length of the projection of <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> onto the normal vector is <m>|\comp_{\vn} \overrightarrow{PQ}| = |-\frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}| = \frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}</m>. This means the distance from point <m>Q</m> to the plane <m>p</m> is <m>\frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>

  </exercise>

